04023nam a22006735i 9780271056814DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212011pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710568147 a10.1515/97802710568142doi  a(DE-B1597)583780  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHQ1236.5.I4bK43 2011eb 7aPOL0040002bisacsh04a305.4209542221 aKeating, Christine, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDecolonizing Democracy :bTransforming the Social Contract in India /cChristine Keating. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (168 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Decolonizing Democracy -- t1 Fraternalist and Paternalist Approaches to Colonial Rule -- t2 Resistant Convergences: Anticolonial Feminist Nationalism -- t3 Framing the Postcolonial Social Contract -- t4 Challenging Political Marginalization: The Women's Reservation Bill -- t5 Legal Pluralism and Gender Justice -- tConclusion: Building a Nondomination Contract -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost democratic theorists have taken Western political traditions as their primary point of reference, although the growing field of comparative political theory has shifted this focus. In Decolonizing Democracy, comparative theorist Christine Keating interprets the formation of Indian democracy as a progressive example of a "postcolonial social contract." In doing so, she highlights the significance of reconfigurations of democracy in postcolonial polities like India and sheds new light on the social contract, a central concept within democratic theory from Locke to Rawls and beyond. Keating's analysis builds on the literature developed by feminists like Carole Pateman and critical race theorists like Charles Mills that examines the social contract's egalitarian potential. By analyzing the ways in which the framers of the Indian constitution sought to address injustices of gender, race, religion, and caste, as well as present-day struggles over women's legal and political status, Keating demonstrates that democracy's social contract continues to be challenged and reworked in innovative and potentially more just ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aConstitutional historyzIndia. 0aFeminismzIndia. 0aSocial contract. 0aWomenxLegal status, laws, etc.zIndia. 0aWomen's rightszIndia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civil Rights.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271056814423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271056814.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK